We can write the system of equations as the augmented matrix:

\[
\begin{amatrix}{3}
1 & 1 & 1 & 6 \\
0 & 2 & 3 & 7 \\
0 & 0 & 3 & 3 \\
\end{amatrix}
\]

First, we can perform row operations to get a leading coefficient of 1 in the first column of the second row. We can achieve this by swapping rows R1 and R2:

\[
\begin{amatrix}{3}
0 & 2 & 3 & 7 \\
1 & 1 & 1 & 6 \\
0 & 0 & 3 & 3 \\
\end{amatrix}
\]

Next, we can perform row operations to get zeros below the leading coefficient in the first column. We can achieve this by multiplying R1 by -1 and adding it to R2, and then multiplying R1 by -2 and adding it to R3:

\[
\begin{amatrix}{3}
0 & 2 & 3 & 7 \\
1 & -1& -2& -6\\
0&-2&-6&-12\\
\end{amatrix}
\xrightarrow[]{R_2 = R_2 + (- \frac{1}{2})R_1 }
